Remarks. Shells of this species are scarce in museum collections. The recorded localities are few, but it can be common where it occurs. It is used as food in Sarawak (
Hamli et al. 2013
). The shells of the largest and oldest animals are often severely worn (by abrasion and/or soil acidity) on the apertural side of the spire. The combination of sharp peripheral keel with solely axial sculpture makes this species easily recognized.
